2. Introduction

2.1. Initial remarks

This document describes the analysis of the second round of data from a mouse cross for a modifier screen for ASD.

An F2 intercross between B6 and CAST was performed. The B6 background contains the mutation, Col4a1 which is located on chromosome 8: 11198423-11312826. The ASD phenotype on the B6 background is very severe. When the mutation is crossed on the CAST B6F1 background, the ASD phentype was largely rescued.

See the first analysis report for more informartion.

The analysis steps will follow the same steps as the first analysis, but will use mice from both batches.

3. Data entry

Our first task is to process the primary data in a form that R/qtl can process.

3.1. Preliminary steps

We first load the necessary libraries for statistical analysis, set the cache directory, and set the random number seed so that the results are reproducible.

> library(qtl)
> library(vcd)
> set.seed(40881)
> options(width=132)

3.2. Data entry

Enter the raw data and print the dimensions of the data.

> rawData <- read.table(file="primary/asd3.csv",colClasses="character",
+                       header=FALSE,sep=",")
> dim(rawData)
[1]  197 1460

Now we will try to remove monomorphic markers that do not contribute any information. The first 9 columns are phenotypes, and the rest are genotypes. We will tabulate the genotypes and count the number of genotypes observed, excluding the missing genotypes (denoted by "-").

3.3. Number of variants per marker

> colIdx <- 12:1460
> rowIdx <- 4:197
> nVariants <- apply(rawData[rowIdx,colIdx],2,
+                    function(x) {length(table(x,exclude="-"))})
> table(nVariants)
nVariants
  1   2   3
516 137 796

There are 787 markers with all three expected genotypes (in the previous round there were 784). There are 513 monomorphic markers, and 139 dimorphic markers. There are 4 markers with four alleles. We have to examine these closely.

3.4. List of unique values

We list all the unique values in the table.

> tabAlleles <- apply(rawData[rowIdx,colIdx],2,table,exclude="-")
> unique(unlist(lapply(tabAlleles,names)))
[1] "B" "C" "H"

3.5. Replace extraneous values

We replace the unexpected characters with what we expect.

> replaceValues <- function(x,a,b)
+   {
+     for( i in 1:ncol(x) )
+       {
+         idx <- which(x[,i]==a)
+         if(length(idx)>0)
+           x[idx,i] <- b
+       }
+     x
+   }
> newData <- replaceValues(rawData,"--","-")
> newData <- replaceValues(newData,"B ","B")
> newData <- replaceValues(newData,"C ","C")
> newData[-(1:3),] <- replaceValues(newData[-(1:3),]," ",NA)
> newData[-(1:3),11] <- sub("B","0",newData[-(1:3),11])
> newData[-(1:3),11] <- sub("C","1",newData[-(1:3),11])
> tabAlleles <- apply(newData[rowIdx,colIdx],2,table,exclude="-")
> unique(unlist(lapply(tabAlleles,names)))
[1] "B" "C" "H"

3.6. Write out new data set

We now have only the expected codes in our data.

> write.table(newData,file="asdCross3.csv",quote=FALSE,sep=",",
+             row.names=FALSE,col.names=FALSE)

5. Genome scans

We calculate the genotype probabilities as a preparatory step.

> cr1 <- calc.genoprob(cr1,step=2)

We perform genome scans and 1024 permutations for evaluating significance. All genome scans use linear models which are likely not the best for the categorical phenotypes. We need to discuss and make changes as appropriate.

> out1 <- scanone(cr1,pheno.col=c(2:9,13),method="hk")
> out1x <- scanone(cr1,pheno.col=c(2:9,13),addcovar=as.numeric(cr1$pheno$sex),
+                  method="hk")

We make a dichotomous version of ASD and analyze it. I dichotomized at the median (2). This is better for power, and is consistent with the previous version.

> cr1$pheno$asdBin <- as.numeric(cr1$pheno$asd<=2)
> out1Bin <- scanone(cr1,pheno.col=14,method="hk",model="binary")
> out1xBin <- scanone(cr1,pheno.col=14,addcovar=as.numeric(cr1$pheno$sex),
+                     method="hk",model="binary")
